f a variety of biological approaches to political attitudes and preferences, the authors consider a wide range of topics, including the comparative basis of political behavior, the utility of formal modeling informed by evolutionary theory, the genetic bases of attitudes and behaviors, psychophysiological methods and research, and the wealth of insight generated by recent research on the human brain. Through this approach, the book reveals the biological bases of many previously unexplained variances within the extant models of political behavior. The diversity of methods discussed and variety of issues examined here will make this book of great interest to students and scholars seeking a comprehensive overview of this emerging approach to the study of politics and behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiopolitics. 0aEvolution (Biology) and the social sciences. 0aPolitical sociology. 0aSociobiology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aApicella, Coren L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoardman, Jason D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrosnan, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCesarini, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawes, Christopher T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDruckman, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEaves, Lindon J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowler, James H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatemi, Peter K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatemi, Peter K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeath, Andrew C., e